This TiddlyWiki has being developed by People, Systems and Things [[PSaT.com.au|hettp://PSaT.com.au]] [[Contact us|http://psat.com.au/contact-us/]] if you see the potential to use TiddlyWiki for business or private use. TiddlyWiki specific notes are to be developed [[here|http://psat.com.au/tiddlywiki/]].

More from [[TiddlyWiki.com|http://tiddlywiki.com]]

~TiddlyWiki is a rich, interactive tool for manipulating complex data with structure that doesn't easily fit into conventional tools like spreadsheets or wordprocessors.


~TiddlyWiki is designed to fit around your brain, helping you deal with the things that won't fit. The fundamental idea is that information is more useful and reusable if we cut it up into the smallest semantically meaningful chunks -- tiddlers|-- and give them titles so that they can be structured with links, tags, lists and macros. Tiddlers use a ~WikiText notation that concisely represents a wide range of text formatting and hypertext features. ~TiddlyWiki aims to provide a fluid interface for working with tiddlers, allowing them to be aggregated and composed into longer narratives.


People love using ~TiddlyWiki. Because it can be used without any complicated server infrastructure, and because it is open source, it has brought unprecedented freedom to everyone to keep their precious information under their own control.


~TiddlyWiki was originally created by ~JeremyRuston and is now a thriving open source project with a busy Community of independent developers.

!Saving
TiddlyWiki writes its changes to your local file system, and as a result of standard security in Internet browsers a download process or plugin is required to save details. The Optimum browser is Firefox and the add-on can be found [[here|https://addons.mozilla.org/en-us/firefox/addon/tiddlyfox/versions/]] The latest version can be used in ~FireFox on the desktop where your need to click on the icon to enable saving for each tiddlywiki, or use Version __1.0alpha18.1-signed.1-signed__ for ~FireFox on Android which will prompt on opening a new tiddlywiki. Installing the Android version needs you to touch to the right to activate the install button.






;I will try and show if then else while until etc.. in the long run

;1. Sequence
:One step following another
:With sequence it commonly stops when you reach the bottom of a tiddler
*1.1 Left to right, Top then down the wiki text, the first item is displayed above the next etc... down the page
:Note new line vs paragraphs
*1.2 Using list and a filter to get a sequence of items displayed or acted on
:Using a list for sequence it commonly stops when the members of the list finish/are exhausted, it then moves to the next line of the current tiddler until you reach the bottom of a tiddler
:This can be impacted by "Includes" see below.
;2. Iteration
:Repeat for each item in a set, ending when no more items are in the set or some condition is true/false
*2.1 Using the list widget with a filter that has 0 or more members 
*2.2 An iteration can be ordered using sorting
*2.3 There are many ways to re-iterate, and you can re-iterate Macros, with transclusions and a lot more, most iterations will end with no more members in a list or some other condition.
;3. Sorting
:Choosing the order in which more than one item is listed
*3.1 Filtered lists permit the addition of the sort[fieldname] filter operator which can be used to sort the final list
:Default is title or for tagged items the order in which they appear in the tags list field
:!sort[fieldname] will reverse the order
*3.2 Used with iteration to support the order in which the items are acted on 

;4. Selection/Decision
:using some condition to determine whether to display something or not
*4.1 A list field will list is membership if there are members. otherwise will not
*4.2 If you need to determine if there are one or more (not Zero members), or any other number of something
:You can use the limit[n] filter operator so that limit[1] will display only once if there is one or more members
:?Limit[0] works?
:?Use ? starting line for a different class
*4.3 If you want to test there is no members?
:The emptyMessage is available on the list widget and emptyValue on the set widget
*4.4 What if you want to list the non-members
:Using the ! with the filter operators
:Note default set all regular tiddlers so perhaps filter based on another condition first
*4.5 The reveal widget allows a section to be displayed according to a match including comparisons
:Reveal widgets can also be nested
*4.6 Simple Comparisons
*4.7 Inclusion/exclusion and other selection tests
*The do nothing case or filter but exclude
*A tiddler but not those it is the prefix of
:`[prefix[tiddlername]suffix[tiddlername]]` is both its prefix and its suffix
*4.8 Selection and decisions can be made based on values that are in variables, Tiddlers, fields and more
:so review ''Using Values and variables'' or ''Setting Values and variables''


;5. Nesting
:This is the process where one set of actions occur within another set of actions, With tiddlywiki nesting can occur for many levels "deep"
:This is how Case and Recursion below, amongst other structures are possible.
*5.1 One implicit example of nesting is a Single ListWidget in a particular tiddler, it is in fact nesting its result in the existing tiddler
*5.2 In most cases anything you write can be nested within something else, and as many deep as you choose.
:However if you nest your current tiddler in the current tiddler you __may__ face infinite recursion (like between two mirrors)
:See 7.x Recursion for intentional use of this ability
*5.3 Example Nesting list widgets

```

<$list filter="filter1">
Do this for each filter1 case
   <$list filter="filter2">
   Do this for each filter2 case
       <$list filter="filter3">
           Do this for each filter3 case
          <$list filter="filter4">
             Do this for each filter4 case
          </$list>
       </$list>
   </$list>
</$list>
```

:''Notes:'' 
*If the number of levels of nesting can vary or is large or unknown using ''recursion'' may be a better solution.
*If transclusion or macro are used to ''include'' additional content these are in effect nested where they are included, and may contain other nesting themselves.
*Each filter applies to the CurrentTiddler as determined by the previous ListWidget unless a variable=//variablename// is set.
*Each filter starts with an assumption you are filtering from all tiddlers, so use a variable or currentTiddler value from the previous List widget for logically nested lists.

;6. Case
:When you want something to occur differently for each case or member in a set
:6.1 A simple list allows you to do something for each member in a list which is a simple example of the "Case" structure.
:In the following example each member of the set becomes the current tiddler and everything in "Do this for this case" will be applied to each tiddler.
```
<$list filter="yourfilter">
Do this for each case
</$list>
```
:6.2 Treating specific cases differently
:note in the below skeleton that the "specific case" tests are nested at the same level within the "yourfilter" outer listWidget
```
<$list filter="yourfilter">
Do this for each case
   <$list filter="specificcase1filter">
       Do this for each specificcase
   </$list>
   <$list filter="specificcase2filter">
       Do this for each specificcase2
   </$list>
</$list>
 
```
:very sophisticated case structures can be built with the power of each list filter, emptyMessage
:examples to follow
*One statement for a subgroup or list of values
*Multiple actions for each case

;7. Recursion
:A process calling itself
*7.1 Using ListWidgets in a tiddler or macro to call itself allows you to perform recursive loops
:For example building a TableOfContents which list the tiddlers tagging the top tiddler, then all tiddlers tagging those, then all tiddlers tagging those...
:The advantage of the list widget is it typically finishes after the last item in the list is processed, ensuring you eventually exit all recursion levels 
:See [[WikiPedia on Recursion|http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recursion]]

;8. Includes
:including content in one location that is found in another
*8.1 Macros
*8.2 Transclusion

;9. Using Values and variables
:Set/Vars/Params
:EmptyValue/EmptyMessage
:Auto seting in lists
:titles of tiddlers vs pseudo titles from lists
;10 Setting Values and variables
:Often values and variables can be set in the context they are used as seen in ''Using Values and variables'', however we often want the user to supply information for our Values and Variables
*Select
*Checkbox
*Edit
*
;11. Accessing last or previous values






At this site We will document some tips and tricks using TiddlyWiki in our own words, but we will not attempt to create just another repository of information on TiddlyWiki, rather we plan to Contribute to the further development of Documentation. We expect to publish some of our own work, perhaps even plugins.

see [[Our TiddlyWiki Project ideas]]

!!!!Technical
*This site is hosted using PHP and the Store script






!!What is so special about TiddlyWiki?

"TiddlyWiki is like the craft material Plasticine for the Digital era". You can make anything out of it. Quite importantly it maintains this ability by avoiding trying to do everything for everyone, it simply focuses on allowing everyone to do anything. As a result there are some compelling uses for tiddlywiki that require the user to develop their knowledge quite a bit before they can rapidly build more sophisticated solutions. This project will endeavor to turbo charge TiddlyWiki users into sophisticated users. 


When you place information into a tiddlywiki you empower this information to be organised, relationships identified, search and manipulation is simplified, it is the best place I can imagine to put data and information that is important to you. So much can be done by the novice with tiddlywiki you may wonder what remains. Further, a tiddlywiki is also like a document, or like a phone app, or an encyclopedia.

!!Is this too big for me?

In todays world of big data, impressive cloud storage and large high speed storage, few people recognise that information and knowledge actually requires very little storage space. For example complete online encyclopedias can store much of the most important knowledge in the world in less space than is required to store video of even a single episode of a TV Show. Software can capture complex relationships and processes in short pieces of code. As a result of this surprising fact, a single tiddlywiki can hold the keys to vast fields of knowledge. It is this realisation that we look to taking tiddlywiki further.

!!What do you know?

Most people have specialist knowledge of some sort, even if it is only their own lived experience. But just consider your occupation, or a hobby, an interest in some field or practice or raising your children and you can see you know things about the world that others near you do not. This is the knowledge of what we will call for short a "Subject Matter Expert" or SME, SME's usually know how to organise what they know well, they understand the content, attributes and relationships of common objects and ideas in their field. If you are in position to capture this expertise for your own use, to share, to develop your understanding further, then you are empowered to expand what you know, maintain a history, increase productivity, reflect on what is important to you and much more.

!!Doing more with what you know

As we said before tiddlywiki allows everyone to do anything. Perhaps it's key limitation is it has too few limitations. As a Subject Mater Expert, SME you know how to organise what you know or at least you understand what is important in your field of interest. It can be quite a jump to craft a tiddlywiki into a form that responds well to your field or interest, after all TiddlyWiki knows nothing about what you know. It is this gap this project aims to bridge, it will do so based on concepts well understood in computer science but not so familiar to the lay person. Fortunately these concepts are quite easy to grasp, have real-world examples and empower so much that the small investment on your part will have substantial returns.

!!Project approach

To bridge this gap between what can be done, and what you can do, this project aims to provide some tools you can add to tiddlywiki that allow you to quickly setup tiddlywiki to cater to your needs. Exactly how we can do this needs us to think a little abstractly for a moment. We are also keen to use a bootstrap approach, where you have the tools to lift yourself up by your own bootstraps. For example, use the tools we provide so you can learn to use the tools we provide.

!!On objects and Concepts

On thing computer science has taught us is we can represent much of "what is" using only two elements, one is an object, the other is the relationships between objects. Lets take a simple object such as a particular hammer, we know it has various attributes, and is has a particularly special relationship with another kind of object, a nail. The relationship we are most familiar with is that hammers are used to drive in nails. Both objects and relationships can have qualities, or what we call attributes. For example your hammer may be a claw hammer, your nail may go into a nail gun. The attribute or nature of relationships can change as well, for example your claw hammer has an additional relationship with nails, it can be used to remove them. Another thing we can see is relationships can be "one to one" or "one to many" (more than one), One key may be able to unlock one door, one hammer can drive in many nails. Even most ideas, processes, concepts even poems can be organised as objects and relationships.

!!TiddlyWiki as it stands

There is no question that TiddlyWiki can handle a representation of any object in a tiddler, even a "sub-tiddler" and any relationship by many methods. However beyond wikitext and tagging, which is very powerful in its own right, there is a learning curve to be climbed. How can we provide a escalator for the climb?

!!Lets get started

What we propose is to provide the tools for people to build reusable objects, define relationships and assign attributes both quickly and easily, but in such a way this can increase in sophistication rapidly. Letting templates be created to kick start the creation of new instances of objects, such as a hammer may be an instance of a tool object. This is likely to empower many more people to achieve great results. In addition we will make it easy for the objects to be shared. Once one SME develops an object with its common attributes and implied relationships, it can be shared with others to record their own objects, or even share the details of specific objects.

Hello everybody,
I just want to let you know that the project who seek to improve the TiddlyWiki documentation structure is not dead. It received green light from Jeremy and others and soon we should have a new docs structure.
Maybe you should take this also into account.
If you want to know more follow the links below:

The GitHub issue page: 
https://github.com/Jermolene/TiddlyWiki5/issues/2912#issuecomment-351554436

The demo site: 
http://morosanuae.tiddlyspot.com/#TiddlyWiki%20Manual

Are you referring to contributing through GItHub? The new structure is not implemented yet, so you'll have to wait a little bit.

Anyway we need good docs about contributing through GitHub, although some people are afraid of it from what I understand.

This will have it's place in the "Helping the community" chapter (book).

I'm no Git guru, or big GitHub user for that matter.
I do use Git a bit for my sysadmin related scripts at work, some html stuff etc.

Real GitHub people please feel free to step in as needed....

The normal flow with GitHub as I understand it is this:

0 - create a GitHub account
1 - 'Clone' or copy an existing 'repository' or set of code and it's historical info into your own account.
2 - (optional) create a 'branch' where you'll work on one concept or feature you want to improve
3 - make the changes you want
4 - go back to the original repository and create a 'pull request' - you're telling the repository owner you've done something they should add back into the master set of code.
5 - discussion takes place on the comments around pull request
6 - revise changes
7 - create new pull request(?)
8 - project owner(s) merge
9 - repeat at step 2

I'm a little hazy how you keep your clone up to date with the master, and the best way to revise pull requests.

Did that help or hurt?

Perhaps this is better - the official docs

https://help.github.com/articles/github-flow/

and for an 'illustrated' version of that

https://guides.github.com/introduction/flow/


I can see where that's pretty intimidating for someone not used to the tools...

I have always had used the following interactive tutorials to teach git:

https://learngitbranching.js.org/
https://try.github.io/levels/1/challenges/1








\define mymacro(parm)
:`$parm$` $parm$
:`"$parm$"` "$parm$"
:`{{$parm$}}` {{$parm$}}
:`[[$parm$]]` [[$parm$]]
:`<<outside-variable>>` <<outside-variable value>>
: $ ( outside-variable ) $  $(outside-variable)$
:`$(outside-variable)$`  $(outside-variable)$ (special case of being able to place outside variable inside the code ticks)

\end

;Overview
*This tiddler is a single page reference work, or cheatsheet that brings together some essential knowledge in becoming a TiddlyWiki expert.
*Work is under-way to help introduce TiddlyWiki to new users, but this documentation comes as a result of someone at the end of that journey documenting essential facts.
*If you are not aware of some of the issues here you may find using tiddlywiki a little frustrating as you try and do more and more advanced things, 
*Once you understand what the headings below refer to, return to this when you are not getting the results you expect in each of these areas.
*For more details and examples, see: http://pv5.tiddlyspot.com
;See [[Table|Variables, Parameters and transclusions - table]]
:[[Original source of Inspiration|http://tobibeer.github.io/tb5/#Variables%20vs.%20Parameters]]

;Recommendation
:This resource can be used in two key ways
#Read and digest every detail in your learning path
#Lookup the subheading that relates to an area you are having difficulty with.

<h2>''Using this reference''</h2>

://If you know where you wish to use a value, variable, transclusion etc... select from one of the below subheadings to learn how to use it there//
://but what about when I am trying to achieve something?//
* ''Within wikiText'' 
:Shows what is valid in the body of a tiddler and wherever the content will be "wikified" (Eg Wikify or after transclusion)
* ''Within Filters''
:Shows what is valid inside filter statements in widgets and 'Filtered transclusions'.
* ''Within HTML and Widgets''  - Parameters and Attributes
: HTML can be used in ~TiddlyWiki this shows how to use ~TiddlyWiki values in HTML tags / attributes
*''Within HTML Content''
: This section is about what you can place between HTML tags
* ''Additional features within macro definitions / macro body''
://That is what is valid on the line after `/define macroname()` or until the `/end` statement.//
* ''Within a Macro call or for a "macro parameter"''
: What is valid on a macrocall eg `<<macroname parameters>>` Within a Macro call or for a "macro parameter" ie calling macros, passing parameters to the macro
* ''Concatenating values for use in Macros and Widgets''
: If you read and understand everything documented here you will realise your instinct to try and concatenate more than one value will not work. Here we explain how to do this.
* ''Other special Cases''
: Evans Formulae plugin (you will need to install) introduces the mushroom brackets `(= content =)` which is a way to calculate a value which will then be substituted where the `(= content =)`is placed. Since the values that can be calculated can also be transclusions or (Variables - not working as advertised) eg `<<macrocall "(={{!!count}}=)">>` works.
* ''Core Variables''
:A Small list of variables generated by the "Core" of ~TiddlyWiki
* ''Useful transclusions''
: A small set of useful transclusions populated by the "Core" of ~TiddlyWiki
<hr style="page-break-after: always;">

;Within wikiText
*Single brackets `<htmltag> </htmltag>` delineate html in Wiki text (As per [[HTML standards|https://www.w3schools.com/tags/default.asp]])
*So Double brackets `<<macroorvarname>>` are used to indicate Variables and Macros defined in TiddlyWiki
*and `<$widgetname> and </$widgetname>` are used to delineate tiddlywiki widgets. 
*and `{{tiddlername}} or {{tiddlername!!fieldname}}` are used to delineate tiddlywiki transcludes or can be called text references.
*and `{{tiddlername||templatename}} or {{tiddlername!!fieldname||templatename}}` Transcludes/text references that use a Template tiddler ''More explanation''
*and `{{{ filter }}}` transcludes the result of the filter.
:So in general wiki text, including macros body (not parameters)
* `<<variable>>`
* `{{transclusion}}  {{tiddlername!!fieldname}}`
* `{{{ filter }}}` this transcluds the result of the filter, a "filtered transclusion".
* Note In Wiki Text only `"<<varname>>"` will still evaluate `<<varname>>` and wrap it with double Quotes, unlike when used as the value in a Parameter.
* @@.warn Not in Wiki Text ~~`<variable>`, `"<variable>"`,  `[[<variable>]]`~~@@ 
**//Single `<    >` only work in filters (but does not support parameters).//
*''Keep in mind almost every other section in this reference describes details of what we can include wiki text''
**Eg Variables, Macro calls, Transclusions, Widgets and "Widgets with Filters, and filtered transclusions.
**Also special pragma such as `\define macroname()` to Within macro definitions / macro body at the top of a tiddler.
<hr style="page-break-after: always;">

;Within Filters
*There is no need to include html or widgets in Filters so single bracket versions are used (unlike ''Within wikiText'')
:In Wiki text we must allow `<htmltag></htmltag>` to be identified as they are different from `<<macropname>>`, `<$widgetname></$widgetname>` but not in filters.
:so `<variableormacro> and {tiddlername} or {tiddlername!!fielodname}` are used in filters
*since the above delineate the beginning and end  of a variable or transclusion you leave out a set of `[ ]` in filters.
:eg `filter="[!has<fieldnamevar>]"` or `"filter="[<currentTiddler>backlinks[]]"` `"filter="[subfilter<subfilterdefinition>]"`
:While a variable's 'value', or a macros 'output', can be used as a filter parameter, 'macro parameters' are not supported in filters.
: @@.warn ~~`<macroname parameter>`~~@@ can be used but the parameter is ignored ????? TEST
*Filters are commonly used in widgets which use a filter or subfilter parameter
:The exception is the special triple curly braces `{{{ filterhere }}}` which can be used wherever a transculsion also works. CHECK [[See|https://tiddlywiki.com/#Transclusion%20in%20WikiText]]
*You can provide a filter using a text reference but its whole definition needs to come from the text reference
:eg `filter={{tiddlername}}` or `filter={{tiddlername!!fieldname}}` note: no delimiters other than the curly braces 
:you can not "concatenate" other values into the filter value here
:: @@.warn ~~`filter={{tiddlername}}othervaluevariablemacroortransclusion`~~@@
*Filter can be used to ''concatenate values using filter operators'' - specifically the ''String Operators'' [[see here|https://tiddlywiki.com/#Filter%20Operators]]
:for example

```
<$set name=value filter="[[start]addprefix[prefix-]addsuffix[-suffixText]removesuffix[Text]]">
<<value>>
</$set>
```
:<$set name=value filter="[[start]addprefix[prefix-]addsuffix[-suffixText]removesuffix[Text]]">
<<value>>
</$set>
*If the filter is defined in a macro or variable you can use it in a filter using  
:eg; `"filter="[subfilter<subfilterdefinition>]"`
:TEST `filter={{{ filter }}}`

: ''Filter value examples''
:: `[tag<variable>]` (only single angle brackets, no inner square brackets required!)
:: `[tag{transclusion}]` (only single curly brackets, no inner square brackets required!)
:: @@.warn ~~`[tag[$(variable)$]]`~~@@ ''TEST NOT''
:The following filter examples use parameters, so only work inside the filters, within macros
:: `[$macroParameter$]` (in filters within macros)
:: `[tag[$macroParameter$]]` (in filters within macros) ''TEST''
:: `[tag{$macroParameter$}]` (in filters within macros) ''TEST''
:: `[tag<$macroParameter$>]` (in filters within macros) ''TEST''
<hr style="page-break-after: always;">

;Within Widgets and HTML - Parameters and Attributes
://general [[html element attributes|https://www.w3schools.com/tags/ref_attributes.asp]], including widgets, e.g. `$list $macrocall`//
://Note that because a Macrocall can not have "variables, macros and transcludions" as parameters we use the $macrocall widget where these are permitted//
: `<$widget attribute=<<variable>>/>`
: `<$widget attribute=<<callMacroToComputeValue>>/>`
: `<$widget attribute={{transclusion}}/>`
:`{{!!transclusion}}` a field whos value can also be inside `[[  ]]` if the fields value contains a title.???
: @@.warn ~~`<$widget attribute="prefix-<<variable>>"/>`~~@@ Whole Treated as a literal, no concatenation
: @@.warn ~~`<$widget attribute=[[prefix-<<variable>>]]/>`~~@@  Will reference a tiddler by the name `[[prefix-<<variable>>]]`
: @@.warn ~~`<$widget attribute="prefix-{{transclusion}}"/>`~~@@  Whole Treated as a literal, no concatenation

://Within HTML tags such as `<div style="stylename"></div>`//
://between tags can include wikiText such as  `<div> Wiki Text macros call etc.. here </div>`//
:In an extension of conventional HTML syntax, attributes of html elements/widgets can be specified in several different ways: [[see|https://tiddlywiki.com/#HTML%20in%20WikiText]]
* a literal string `<div style="stylename"></div>`
* a transclusion of a TextReference `<div style={{tiddlername!!fieldname}} ></div>`
* a transclusion of a macro/variable `<div style=<<stylevar>> ></div>`
* as the result of a Filter Expression `<div style={{{ filter }}} ></div>` TEST
:Literal attribute values can use several different styles of quoting:
::No quoting is necessary for values that do not contain spaces eg `attr=value`
::Single quotes eg `attr='value'`
::Double quotes eg `attr="value"`
::Triple double quotes eg `attr="""value"""`
<hr>

;Within HTML Content
:Single brackets `<htmltag> </htmltag>` delineate html in Wiki text (As per HTML standards) ''This section is about what you can place between them''
:Almost anything can be included within HTML content
::However To get the content of an HTML element to be parsed in block mode, the opening tag must be followed by two linebreaks.
:For example the html tag `<hr>` for horizontal line

```
<hr>

Wiki Text here
```
::Without the two linebreaks (one on `<hr>` line and one after}, the tag content will be parsed in inline mode which means that block mode formatting such as wikitext tables, lists and headings is not recognised.

:Review ''Within Widgets and HTML - Parameters and Attributes'' for content inside HTML tags
<hr style="page-break-after: always;">

;Within macro definitions / macro body
://As macros are simply parameterised variables ie: you can pass them __parameters__, a variable's value can be inserted using the same techniques as ????macroname's.//
:In macros we often want to pass a parameter who's value replaces something inside the macro
:Since macros have parameters, and text substitutions are helpful, macros can contain additional reverences to values, in addition to all those as needed ''Within wikiText'', ''Within Filters'', ''Within a Macro call or for a "macro parameter"''.
:The various `$ $` forms are substitutions, they are simply replaced with the value before any other evaluation.
:Macros help us in  ''Concatenating values for use in Macros and Widgets'', because the macros output can be referenced by name through out ~TiddlyWiki
:: eg; `<<macroname>>` is replaced with the output of the macro name.
:Also the `<<__...__>>` ''Parameter-as-variable'' provides access to a parameter defined in the macro parameters list [[Reference|https://tiddlywiki.com/#Macro%20Definitions%20in%20WikiText]] so you can use a parameter in the same way you use a variable.
::This exposes macro parameters as variables so that it is possible to safely refer to parameters that may contain quotation marks. 
::A construction like `<div attr="$param$">` fails if the parameter contains a double quote. In the core "triple double quotes" are used <small>which only fails when the parameter string ends with a double quotation mark</small>
::The new double underscore syntax to refer to parameters as variables doesnâ€™t obviate the need for the usual $-delimited format. It can still make sense to use the $-delimited format when you really do want text substitution to take place. :Concatenations can also be achieved via filter operators such as addprefix, and the filter operator in the `<$set widget`.
::As a general rule of thumb, if the output of a macro is intended to be wikified then it is usually appropriate to refer to parameters as variables. If the output of the macro is not intended to be wikified (eg constructing a tiddler title from several parts) then its usually best to use text subsitution.[[Discussion|https://groups.google.com/forum/?hl=en#!topic/tiddlywiki/QzvZD9GGTbg]]
:eg `<<__paramname__>>`
:The opposite to Parameter-as-variable, ie ''Variable-as-parameter'' use a variable as if it were a parameter, for a substitution is the `$(outside-variable)$` format.


:''Defining Macros''

```
\define macroname(parameternames) on a single line
```

:or multiple lines;

```
\define macrocname(parameternames)
Something that results in output like this line
\end
```

:We thus use $parametername$ and this is replaced exactly with the value of parametername, as a result you may need to wrap this with some delimiters such as `value="$parametername$"`
: `$macroParameter$`, `"$macroParameter$"`, `[[$macroParameter$]]` Simple replacement
: `$(variable)$` (references a variable from the context of the calling macro)

Next.. more on the $(...)$ syntax

<span style="page-break-after: always;"/>

*The $(...)$ syntax means "substitute the variable defined before this macro was invoked".
: `<$widget attribute="prefix-$macroParameter$"/>` with simple replacement can concatinate
: `<$widget attribute=$macroParameter$/>` (unsafe when having spaces) use Single-quote, double-quote or "triple double-quote"
: @@.warn ~~`$variable$`, `"$variable$"`, `[[$variable$]]`~~@@ ?
::$name$ for a macro parameter transclusion and $(name)$ for a variable transclusion.
:However inside a macro is also treated as wiki text so see ''Within wikiText'' above as they also apply, and in filters inside macros ''Within Filters'' applies. If widgets are used 
:''Illustrated here''

<$set name=outside-variable value="value from outside">

<<mymacro "Simpletiddler">>

</$set>

```
\define mymacro(parm)
:`$parm$` $parm$
:`"$parm$"` "$parm$"
:`{{$parm$}}` {{$parm$}}
:`[[$parm$]]` [[$parm$]]
:`<<outside-variable>>` <<outside-variable value>>
: $&#8203;(outside-variable)&#8203;$  $(outside-variable)$
:`$(outside-variable)$`  $(outside-variable)$ (special case of being able to place outside variable inside the code ticks)

\end
<$set name=outside-variable value="value from outside">

<<mymacro "Simpletiddler">>

</$set>
```

<hr style="page-break-after: always;">

;Within a Macro call or for a "macro parameter"
://calling macros, passing parameters to the macro//
:''to include parameter names''
:A macro can simply be called with `<<macroname>>`
:Or provide the call with parameters `<<macroname parameters>>`
:__However the ways in which you can format ''the parameters have some rules''__
::If some of these rules make it difficult to pass the parameters you want consider the following approaches
:::Use the widget `<$macrocall $name=macroname ...` so that methods available in "Within Widgets and HTML'' - Parameters and Attributes become available
:::Consider if the value need not be passed to the macro if the macro can reference that value on its own, so that methods available in "''Within macro definitions / macro body"" can be used.
::If there is no white space you can just provide the name eg `<<macroname field-name>>` 
:::see how field naming standards allow a parameter with out any kind of delimiters.
::If the parameter contains spaces you need to delimit it with `'single quote' "double quote" or """Tripple double quotes"""`
:::This is so you can pass parameters containing  `'single quote' "double quote" or """Tripple double quotes"""` buy using one that is not contained in your parameters value.
:::See 
::Literal Parameter values can use several different styles of quoting: Note the use of ":" not "=".
:::`<<macroname parameter-value>>` No quoting is necessary for values that do not contain spaces (eg parmname=value)
:::`<<macroname 'parameter value'>>` Single quotes (eg parmname:'value')
:::`<<macroname "parameter value">>` Double quotes (eg parmname:"value")
:::`<<macroname """parameter value""">>` Tripe double quotes (eg parmname:"""value""")

<span style="page-break-after: always;"/>

:''Special note(s) Within a Macro call or for a "macro parameter"''
*Since a macro is delimited by `<< >>` do not expect a parameter to contain  `<< >>`  instead you will have to use the macrocall widget.
*Similarly do not expect your parameters to be wikified (Translated into there wiki text equivalent, they will be passed as a literal
:Eg `<<macroname {{!!fieldname}}>>` will pass the value "{&#8203;{!!fieldname}&#8203;}" to the macro parameter, not replace `{{!!fieldname}}` with its value first. 
**Any way in the macro you can reference `{{!!fieldname}}` if you ensure you have the correct currentTiddler value, or use wikify to ''capture its value'' before changing the currentTiddler.
**in the above example this is an unnamed parameter
**Named parameters can be passed using `<<macroname parmname:value parmname2:"value with space">>` `TEST`
::See the $macrocall widget to help when you want to do this
*Remember macros can can be used as a parameter values for macros but only in widgets (especially useful here is the $macrocall widget)
:eg `<$tiddler tiddler=<<macroname>> />` 
:Note in some widgets we can close with "/>" rather than </$widgetname> Usually when we do not care about what the Widget contains.
:Often we place additional 'code' or Wiki Text between the opening and closing of a widget eg `<$list listparams>additional content</$list>` and `<$set name= value= >additional content</$list>`
:So this means the $macrocall widget, allows us to pass the result of one macro to another as a parameter
::Eg `<$macrocall $name=<<othermacroname>> />`
*We are saying that any macro `<<macroname>>` existing or created by you with a `/define` can be called instead with the `<$macrocall` widget. 
::So `<<macroname>>` becomes `<$macrocall $name=macroname />`
::and `<<macroname parameters>>` becomes `<$macrocall $name=macroname parameters/>`
:::Why is it $name= instead of name= ?, because you may want to pass a named parameter called "name"
:::Since macros are effectively the same as a variable, the following simply returns the value of the variable `<$macrocall $name=variablename/>`
::Parameters will be handled differently than in a simple macro call as follows;
:://See ''Literal Parameter values'' values above Note the use of "=" not ":".//
::`parmname={{tiddler}}` parameter equals the contents of the text field in tiddlername
::`parmname={{tiddler!!fieldname}}` parameter equals the contents of the fieldname in tiddlername
::`parmname=<<macroorvariablename>> ` parameter equals the value returned from the macro or variable name
:: `<<macro param:"$macroParameter$">>` (only inside macro or if this macro call is inside another macro with the "macroParameter")
:: @@.warn ~~`<<macro <<variable>> >>`~~@@ Variable will not be evaluated and macro will break on seeing `>>`
:: `<$macrocall $name=macro variablename=<<variable>> />` must know variable name in macro definition
:: @@.warn ~~`<<macro "<<variable>>" >>`~~@@  Variable will not be evaluated and will be literally "`<<variable>>`"
:: `<$macrocall $name=macro variablename=<<variable>> />` must know variable name in macro definition, `<< >>` acts as delimiter so no Quotes required, would become a literal.
:: @@.warn ~~`<<macro param:<<variable>> >>`~~@@  Variable will not be evaluated
:: `<$macrocall $name=macro param=<<variable>>  />`  must know variable name in macro definition,`<< >>`  must know variable name,acts as delimiter so no Quotes required, would become a literal.
:: @@.warn ~~`<<macro {{transclusion}}>>`~~@@  Transclusion will not be evaluated
:: `<$macrocall $name=macro param={{transclusion}}  />`  `{{ }}` acts as delimiter so no Quotes required, otherwise would become a literal.
:: @@.warn ~~`<<macro param:{{transclusion}}>>`~~@@ Transclusion will not be evaluated
:: `<$macrocall $name=macro param={{transclusion}}  />`  `{{ }}` acts as delimiter so no Quotes required, otherwise would become a literal.
<hr style="page-break-after: always;">

; Concatenating values for use in Macros and Widgets
:Why would you use concatination?
*One common use is to generate a tiddler name to use as a state field that includes the current tiddler name.
::The Qualify macro provides a short cut for this `<<qualify $:/state/tiddler>>` will generate a title such as `$:/state/tiddler--1383354177`
::The number is a hash of the currentTiddler title and can be regenerated 
:::eg with the same "currentTiddler" `<<qualify $:/temp/state>>` will generate `$:/temp/state--1383354177`
: If you read and understand everything documented here you will realise your instinct to try and concatenate more than one value will not work. Here we explain how to do this. 
:For example `value="<<variableormacro>>{{transclusion}}Text"` used in a widget parameter including with the $macrocall widget, does not work. 
*In this case you can see that the value="a literal unevaluated version" so it will return precisely `<<variableormacro>>{{transclusion}}Text` which is unlikely what you intended.
:Also consider `value=<<variableormacro>>{{transclusion}}` used in a widget parameter including with the $macrocall widget, does not work either.
*Another way to look at it is as `value=<<variableormacro>>` and `value={{transclusion}}` works the `<<  >>` and `{{  }}` are acting to delineate the beginning and end of the value, combining them is like providing more than one beginning and end to the value and causes errors.
:use the following methods to concatenate a number of values after first evaluating them
*With the Wikify widget

```
<$wikify name=varname text="<<variableormacro>>{{transclusion}}Text">
<<varname>> valid until wikify closed
</$wikify>

```
*Concatenating Within Macro definitions

```
\define varname() <<variableormacro>>{{transclusion}}Text
```
:Remember here the following also work Within Macro definitions (only)
::`$parametername$`
::`$(externalvariable)$`
::''Note'' the values differentiated by "$" signs are substituted before being evaluated so examples such as `[[$parametername$]]` and `{{$(externalvariable)$}}` should work TEST
::`<<__parametername__>>` 

*Concatenating Within Filters
:see ''concatenate values using filter operators'' in the ''Within Filters'' section to use ''String Filter operators''.
:for example using the SetWidget `filter=` parameter.

;Note in the below table; 
*''~WikiText, Widget Content, HTML Content, macro definition and whole of filter parameter'' are effectively the same thing if we take account of the special macro parameters.
*The only differences are in Filters and Widget/HTML Parameters.
*While `<<macrocalls parameters>>` are also limited use `<$macrocall` widget and all of these disappear.

:In the above table a ''yes'' indicates it works and to ''use the format example''
:If the cell contains an `alternative format` it means ''yes'' but use the format displayed instead.
:If the cell is blank it means ''No'', If it contains ''No'' it indicates ''No'' but many may think it would be possible.

There was a[[ discussion|https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/tiddlywiki/_XFACMURcv4]] in the google group, asking if TiddlyWiki was hacking, Coding or mark-up?, Some thoughts of mine on this, that may offer another perspective. I was a hobby programmer before I left school, then a professional Analyst/Programmer in my early career, and I have always being a conceptual systems thinker, programming solutions for my whole career.

To me programming is the encoding of algorithms, instructions on a piece of paper are good enough for this, but computer programming uses computers to do so, so yes Tiddlywiki is a platform in which to program or capture algorithms which we can make interactive and includes storage and presentation.

Is TiddlyWiki or its Wiki Text a programming language?, I do not think it is a complete language and since it can incorporate JavaScript, and leverages HTML and CSS does it need to would be a valid question. This is in part why I call it a platform. Never the less perhaps there is value in the community ensuring it is a complete programming language of its own, ideally leveraging another language.

While it may not be a complete language it has a number of elements that are "high level language" components. The use of filters and lists allow us to define a set which is then iterated for us rather than us writing the code within that. Writing macros and Importing plugins allow use to build or import higher levels of abstract logic, process and interface control objects.

TiddlyWiki is a "platform" because it brings together all the essential features needs to encode algorithms including alternative ways to present information/data, a highly customisable user interface, the ability to serve it to a network or the world as well as a basis to build a database, build sophisticated relationships and hierarchies, interact with other resources and websites, import and export almost anything, and unlike most other platforms in this space it can also be self contained, a more than minimal Quine, or simply a stand alone document.

Whilst they have being around for a long time in the last decade the Information Technology community has expanded and a new emphasis has being placed on Systems Thinking, Design thinking and UX (user interface). TiddlyWiki is both a playground and a platform through which to exercise both to a high level.

Given the TiddlyWiki platform is so versatile I would describe my self as a designer, designing solutions, capturing information and algorithms on the TiddlyWiki platform. Except for people who are unaware of the platform any one who uses TiddlyWiki is likely to be a designer as well.

!!Documentation
;This tiddler stores relevant information in the Wiki Manager
:The Wiki-tiddler records critical information about this TiddlyWiki instance
::This information allows access to this tiddlers critical settings
::describing it's purpose or function in relation to other wikis in your network
::Generates the wiki-tiddler <<wiki-tiddler>>
:The Wiki Manager also registers this wiki in a unique tiddler which can then be exported to other wikis (Specifically the Core)
::Thus other wikis can maintain a list of registered wikis and obtain critical information about each it is aware of
:We recommend registering each Wiki you create and import this to a central distribution wiki
::Then all existing registered Wikis can be exported from the central distribution wiki, and imported to any other wiki in your network
::Thus all your registered wikis can access information about all your other registered wiki
</$wikify>
</$wikify>
